    <!-- Strings for WHO percentiles information -->
    <string name="titulo_info_percentiles">What are percentiles?</string>
    <string name="info_percentiles_oms">This application uses the growth references from the <b>World Health Organization (WHO)</b> to calculate BMI percentiles in children aged 5 to 19 years.\n\n<b>What does the percentile mean?</b>\nThe percentile indicates what percentage of children of the same age and sex have a lower BMI. For example:\n• 50th percentile: Typical BMI (half have lower BMI)\n• 85th percentile: Only 15% have higher BMI\n• 95th percentile: Only 5% have higher BMI\n\n<b>WHO interpretation:</b>\n• &lt;3: Underweight\n• 3–84: Healthy weight\n• 85–96: Overweight\n• ≥97: Obesity\n\n<b>Important:</b> This application uses the growth references from the <b>World Health Organization (WHO)</b> to calculate BMI percentiles in children aged 5 to 19 years.\n\n<b>What does the percentile mean?</b>\nThe percentile indicates what percentage of children of the same age and sex have a lower BMI. For example:\n• 50th percentile: Typical BMI (half have lower BMI)\n• 85th percentile: Only 15% have higher BMI\n• 95th percentile: Only 5% have higher BMI\n\n<b>WHO interpretation:</b>\n• &lt;3: Underweight\n• 3–84: Healthy weight\n• 85–96: Overweight\n• ≥97: Obesity\n\n<b>Important:</b> These measurements are for guidance only and do not by themselves represent the health status of the child or adolescent. If in doubt, always consult your pediatrician </string>
